<methodology slug="aws-s3-storage">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>infra</group>
    <domain>infrastructure-engineer</domain>
    <summary>S3 bucket security, encryption, lifecycle policies, and cross-region replication with public access blocking and cost optimization through intelligent tiering.</summary>
    <category>cloud</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
    <tags>
      <tag>s3</tag>
      <tag>storage</tag>
      <tag>aws</tag>
      <tag>encryption</tag>
      <tag>lifecycle</tag>
    </tags>
    <tools>
      <tool>claude-code</tool>
    </tools>
    <languages>
      <language>terraform</language>
      <language>cloudformation</language>
    </languages>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>AWS S3 Storage: Security, Encryption, Lifecycle Policies, and Replication</title>

    <summary>S3 bucket security, encryption, lifecycle policies, and cross-region replication best practices. The concrete rule is: always block all public access at bucket AND account level; always enable default encryption (SSE-KMS for sensitive data, SSE-S3 for general); always configure lifecycle rules to abort incomplete multipart uploads within 7 days and transition objects to cheaper storage classes.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>S3 misconfiguration (public access, missing encryption) is among the top causes of cloud data breaches. Lifecycle policies eliminate unbounded storage growth — unmanaged buckets accumulate incomplete multipart uploads and orphaned versions that cost money without delivering value. As of April 2026, SSE-C is disabled by default for new buckets.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Creating any S3 bucket (security defaults must be applied)</item>
        <item>Designing lifecycle rules for cost optimization (Standard → STANDARD-IA → Glacier)</item>
        <item>Setting up Cross-Region Replication (CRR) for disaster recovery</item>
        <item>Configuring bucket policies for cross-account access or HTTPS enforcement</item>
        <item>Choosing between SSE-S3, SSE-KMS, and DSSE-KMS encryption</item>
        <item>Integrating S3 with CloudFront (use OAC, not legacy OAI)</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>CloudFront distribution configuration beyond S3 OAC — use aws-architecture-services</item>
        <item>Athena or Glue data pipeline patterns — those are analytics concerns, not storage concerns</item>
        <item>EBS or EFS storage decisions — different services for block/file storage</item>
        <item>GCP Cloud Storage — use gcp-storage methodology</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="public-access-blocking">
      <p>Public access blocking at account and bucket level with Object Ownership controls.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Block all public access at both account level (S3 Block Public Access) and individual bucket level; set Object Ownership to BucketOwnerEnforced (disables ACLs); never grant public read via bucket policy.</statement>
        <rationale>S3 misconfiguration (public access) is among the top causes of cloud data breaches. Account-level blocking provides a backstop even if per-bucket settings are misconfigured. ACLs are a legacy mechanism superseded by bucket policies.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="encryption">
      <p>Encryption options with SSE-S3, SSE-KMS, DSSE-KMS, and April 2026 SSE-C changes.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Enable SSE-KMS with a customer-managed KMS key for buckets containing sensitive, regulated, or production data; use SSE-S3 (AES-256) for general non-sensitive buckets; enable S3 Bucket Keys to reduce KMS API call cost by up to 99%.</statement>
        <rationale>SSE-KMS provides audit trails of key usage (CloudTrail), key rotation, and access policy control. SSE-S3 is free and requires no key management. Bucket Keys batch multiple object operations into a single KMS call.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Starting April 2026: SSE-C (customer-provided keys) is disabled by default for new buckets. If SSE-C is required, explicitly enable it via PutBucketEncryption API before any SSE-C upload.</statement>
        <rationale>AWS changed the default to prevent misconfigured SSE-C usage where key management falls entirely on the customer with no AWS-side recovery. Teams migrating workloads must re-enable it explicitly.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="bucket-policy">
      <p>Bucket policies for HTTPS enforcement and VPC endpoint integration.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Add a bucket policy denying all s3:* actions where aws:SecureTransport is false; this enforces HTTPS for all access including IAM principals with s3:GetObject permission.</statement>
        <rationale>HTTP requests to S3 transmit data and credentials in cleartext. The SecureTransport condition denies HTTP even if IAM policies grant access, enforcing encryption in transit at the bucket level.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Deny HTTP access with SecureTransport condition">
        <code lang="json"><![CDATA[
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [{
    "Sid": "DenyHTTP",
    "Effect": "Deny",
    "Principal": "*",
    "Action": "s3:*",
    "Resource": [
      "arn:aws:s3:::BUCKET_NAME",
      "arn:aws:s3:::BUCKET_NAME/*"
    ],
    "Condition": {
      "Bool": { "aws:SecureTransport": "false" }
    }
  }]
}
]]></code>
      </example>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use VPC Gateway endpoints for S3 access from EC2, ECS, Lambda, and EKS; configure endpoint policies to restrict access to specific bucket ARNs.</statement>
        <rationale>Gateway endpoints are free and route S3 traffic over the AWS backbone rather than the public internet. Endpoint policies prevent the endpoint from being used to access unauthorized buckets.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <antipattern title="Public bucket via policy or ACL">
        <description>S3 buckets with public read access enabled via bucket policy or ACL.</description>
        <reason>Public buckets are indexed by search engines and security scanners within minutes of creation. Even accidentally exposed sensitive files become permanently cached and accessible.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="lifecycle-policies">
      <p>Lifecycle policies for storage class transitions, multipart upload cleanup, and cost optimization.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Always add a lifecycle rule to abort incomplete multipart uploads after 7 days; add rules to expire non-current object versions and delete expired object delete markers.</statement>
        <rationale>Incomplete multipart uploads accumulate indefinitely without a cleanup rule, silently adding storage cost. Non-current versions from versioned buckets accumulate without expiration rules — one bucket can grow to 10x the logical object size.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Transition objects to Standard-IA after 30 days (minimum), Glacier Instant Retrieval after 90 days, and Glacier Deep Archive after 365 days for logs and audit data; respect the 30-day minimum between transitions.</statement>
        <rationale>Standard-IA costs 58% less than Standard but charges per GB retrieval and has a 30-day minimum storage charge. Transitioning too early (under 30 days) incurs early deletion fees that exceed the savings.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Enable S3 Intelligent-Tiering for buckets with unknown or unpredictable access patterns; enable the Archive and Deep Archive tiers for additional cost reduction on rarely accessed data.</statement>
        <rationale>Intelligent-Tiering monitors access patterns and automatically moves objects between tiers with no retrieval charges. It eliminates the need to predict access patterns for lifecycle rules.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="versioning">
      <p>Versioning configuration with MFA Delete protection.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Enable versioning on all buckets containing production data or Terraform state; enable MFA Delete for buckets with compliance or financial data to prevent accidental version deletion.</statement>
        <rationale>Versioning protects against accidental overwrites and deletes. MFA Delete adds a second factor to permanent version deletion — without it, a compromised access key can delete all versions permanently.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="cross-region-replication">
      <p>Cross-Region Replication (CRR) configuration for disaster recovery with RTC and delete marker control.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Enable CRR (Cross-Region Replication) for disaster recovery buckets with Replication Time Control (RTC) when RPO is under 15 minutes; source and destination must both have versioning enabled; configure an IAM replication role with least-privilege.</statement>
        <rationale>Without RTC, replication time is best-effort (typically under 15 minutes but not guaranteed). RTC provides a 99.99% SLA for 15-minute replication, required for compliance-driven RPO targets.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Configure delete marker replication only when you need deletes to propagate to the replica; by default, delete markers are not replicated, preserving the replica as an independent backup.</statement>
        <rationale>By default, CRR does not replicate delete markers — if a source object is deleted, the replica remains intact. This is correct for DR buckets. Enable delete marker replication only for active-active synchronization scenarios.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <antipattern title="Incomplete multipart uploads without cleanup">
        <description>Buckets without a lifecycle rule to abort incomplete multipart uploads.</description>
        <reason>Multipart uploads that are started but never completed remain as invisible partial uploads charged at standard S3 rates. A single misconfigured client can accumulate thousands of partial uploads in days.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="security-defaults-checklist">
      <p>Security baseline verification and pre-deployment checklist for new S3 buckets.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Verify on every new bucket: Block Public Access enabled (4 settings), Object Ownership = BucketOwnerEnforced, default encryption configured (SSE-KMS or SSE-S3), bucket policy with aws:SecureTransport = false deny rule.</statement>
        <rationale>These four settings are the minimum security baseline for any S3 bucket. Missing any one creates a vulnerability: public access, ACL-based data leaks, unencrypted objects, or plaintext HTTP access.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>For production buckets: enable versioning, enable S3 access logging to a separate audit bucket, enable CloudTrail data events, verify SSE-KMS with customer-managed key and S3 Bucket Keys enabled.</statement>
        <rationale>Versioning enables point-in-time recovery. Access logging and CloudTrail data events are required for compliance audits (SOC2, PCI) to prove access to specific objects at specific times.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="data-management-checklist">
      <p>Data management checklist for lifecycle rules, versioning, and SSE-C transition.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Configure at minimum: abort incomplete multipart uploads after 7 days, transition non-current versions to Standard-IA after 30 days, expire non-current versions after 90 days, delete expired object delete markers.</statement>
        <rationale>These four lifecycle rules prevent unbounded bucket growth from three common accumulation patterns: aborted uploads, old versions, and orphaned delete markers.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>For SSE-C: verify it is explicitly enabled via PutBucketEncryption after April 2026 for any buckets that require customer-provided keys; audit existing SSE-C buckets before the deadline.</statement>
        <rationale>AWS disabled SSE-C by default for new buckets starting April 2026. Teams migrating or creating new buckets requiring SSE-C must explicitly opt in — silent failure otherwise.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="replication-access-checklist">
      <p>Replication and access verification checklist for CRR setup and IAM roles.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>For CRR: confirm versioning on source and destination, IAM replication role with s3:ReplicateObject and s3:ReplicateDelete, destination bucket policy allowing the source role, KMS key sharing if encrypted.</statement>
        <rationale>CRR silently fails if any prerequisite is missing — there is no blocking error at configuration time. Replication metrics and CloudWatch alarms on replication failures are required to detect misconfiguration.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <antipattern title="Production buckets without lifecycle rules">
        <description>S3 buckets in production without any lifecycle rules configured.</description>
        <reason>Unmanaged buckets accumulate costs from three sources: incomplete multipart uploads, non-current versions (if versioned), and expired delete markers. A single active application can generate hundreds of GB of orphaned data per month.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
  </content>
</methodology>
